{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0111f2f0-44e0-11ed-87af-3b7ad318f3f8","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"06bb31c6-89aa-4cfa-a1a7-b3b40f033d3e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The Efficient Markets Hypothesis Versus No Arbitrage","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"9432ae9c-ed6c-46c8-a6c0-a7824e061e88"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"2c52db3c-4c60-4853-b219-35b85492d25a","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"There is an important distinction between the efficient markets hypothesis and the notion of no arbitrage that we introduced in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"7cc55b1f-c6ef-4541-b683-467c9b7388b6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Chapter 3","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"eca039c0-44e0-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":". An arbitrage opportunity is a situation in which two securities (or portfolios) with ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"identical","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" cash flows have different prices. Because anyone can earn a sure profit in this situation by buying the low-priced security and selling the high-priced one, we expect investors to exploit and eliminate these opportunities immediately. Thus, arbitrage opportunities will not be found.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"23451d86-65e7-4452-b78f-af2e1531e578"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"23984d4d-8ca6-4c1f-ad83-c48269dc710e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The efficient markets hypothesis states that the best estimate of the value of a share of stock is its market price. That is, investorsâ€™ own estimates of value are not as accurate as the market price. But that does not mean that the market price always correctly estimates the value of a share of stock. There is a difference between the best estimate and being correct. Thus, there is no reason to expect the market price to always assess value accurately; rather, the price is best viewed as an approximation. However, because the price is the best estimate, the efficient market hypothesis implies that you cannot tell which prices overestimate and which underestimate the true value of the stock.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"6607982a-3c3a-4566-b366-e34923b888f7"}]}]}]},{"cssClass":"aside-group Sidebar_1Aside","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"8246a888-fdf6-4f70-bdea-52cef92f8102","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Concept Check","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"e42654d4-e614-4388-9cad-6916b356ae35"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":5},"ref":"d658db0c-3855-47c2-8282-ac2729b906e4","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"3f8c240c-fcf4-4c06-9a1d-7555d3c560e4","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d82c4dbf-b74a-49c5-a5e0-f041448367d2","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"State the efficient markets hypothesis.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"543d9a32-1648-4613-b67f-354680c